00:12:13,110 --> 00:12:15,296
So the time to act is now.

255
00:12:15,296 --> 00:12:16,188
WOMAN: [INAUDIBLE]

256
00:12:16,188 --> 00:12:17,230
PETE BOUCHARD: Oh, sorry.

257
00:12:17,230 --> 00:12:18,540
My bad.

258
00:12:18,540 --> 00:12:19,420
It would help.

259
00:12:19,420 --> 00:12:19,950
[LAUGHTER]

260
00:12:19,950 --> 00:12:23,478
So when we think about it,
now is the future in the sense

261
00:12:23,478 --> 00:12:25,270
that if we don't do
something about it now,

262
00:12:25,270 --> 00:12:26,500
the future is predecided.

263
00:12:26,500 --> 00:12:28,960
And again, in my limited
knowledge of the human psyche,

264
00:12:28,960 --> 00:12:31,630
I've gone into a little bit
of research on this too.

265
00:12:31,630 --> 00:12:35,070
I took a course in Climate
Communication at Bentley

266
00:12:35,070 --> 00:12:38,040
a few years ago, with a
great professor, by the way.

267
00:12:38,040 --> 00:12:40,410
And shifting baseline
is one of the things

268
00:12:40,410 --> 00:12:42,490
that the human mind goes
right to immediately.

269
00:12:42,490 --> 00:12:44,940
Our grandparents' climate
is not our climate and not

270
00:12:44,940 --> 00:12:46,860
the climate of the future too.

271
00:12:46,860 --> 00:12:51,700
So when we actually
engage with people,

272
00:12:51,700 --> 00:12:53,850
you have to take
that into account.

273
00:12:53,850 --> 00:12:58,330
Climate change is something that
they perceive, but it's changed.

274
00:12:58,330 --> 00:13:01,840
And right here at MIT, they
did research many years ago.

275
00:13:01,840 --> 00:13:06,420
And it takes about five years,
in general, before temperatures

276
00:13:06,420 --> 00:13:07,570
become unremarkable.

277
00:13:07,570 --> 00:13:09,040
So you hit 78 in Christmas.

278
00:13:09,040 --> 00:13:09,670
Big deal.

279
00:13:09,670 --> 00:13:12,850
Becomes normal after a
period of five years.

280
00:13:12,850 --> 00:13:14,620
It's normalized, unfortunately.

281
00:13:14,620 --> 00:13:18,360
Climate change is also a
cultural cognition thing.

282
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:22,160
Unconscious process,
which causes

283
00:13:22,160 --> 00:13:24,660
people to shape their beliefs
to dispute on disputed matters

284
00:13:24,660 --> 00:13:26,730
of fact, based on their values.

285
00:13:26,730 --> 00:13:31,840
So there's obviously, the
hype with the fake news.

286
00:13:31,840 --> 00:13:34,720
The planet is warming
at an alarming rate,

287
00:13:34,720 --> 00:13:37,980
not seen in thousands of years,
perhaps, millions of years.

288
00:13:37,980 --> 00:13:40,343
And everybody's an
expert on this too.

289
00:13:40,343 --> 00:13:42,510
And there's another part
of it that I won't go into.

290
00:13:42,510 --> 00:13:45,260
It's attribute substitution,
which is essentially,

291
00:13:45,260 --> 00:13:47,850
if it's 90 degrees today, of
course, the climate is changing.

292
00:13:47,850 --> 00:13:48,480
It's very warm.

293
00:13:48,480 --> 00:13:50,750
But if it's 20 below tomorrow--

294
00:13:50,750 --> 00:13:51,808
are you insane?

295
00:13:51,808 --> 00:13:52,350
That's crazy.

296
00:13:52,350 --> 00:13:53,720
Of course, it's not.

297
00:13:53,720 --> 00:13:55,670
Politicians would have
you think that there

298
00:13:55,670 --> 00:13:58,560
are two Americas-- a blue
and a red America, right?

299
00:13:58,560 --> 00:14:01,430
But in essence, there
are six Americas when

300
00:14:01,430 --> 00:14:03,530
we talk about climate change.

301
00:14:03,530 --> 00:14:06,750
There are the people that are
alarmed, that are concerned,

302
00:14:06,750 --> 00:14:08,220
that are cautious.

303
00:14:08,220 --> 00:14:11,743
And then there are a few that
are disengaged, agnostic.

304
00:14:11,743 --> 00:14:12,410
They don't know.

305
00:14:12,410 --> 00:14:15,360
The doubtful ones, too,
and the dismissive ones.

306
00:14:15,360 --> 00:14:19,080
So when you add those up,
that's 27% of the population,

307
00:14:19,080 --> 00:14:21,710
but they get all
of the talk, all

308
00:14:21,710 --> 00:14:23,040
of the chatter on social media.

309
00:14:23,040 --> 00:14:24,630
They're the ones that
always troll, right?

310
00:14:24,630 --> 00:14:26,547
They're the ones that
are always in your face.

311
00:14:26,547 --> 00:14:27,990
They want you to disengage.

312
00:14:27,990 --> 00:14:29,232
They want you to back away.

313
00:14:29,232 --> 00:14:31,440
They don't want you to be
a part of the conversation.

314
00:14:31,440 --> 00:14:33,540
They want to be
front and center.

315
00:14:33,540 --> 00:14:37,130
But the vast majority of
people have your back,

316
00:14:37,130 --> 00:14:38,130
when you think about it.

317
00:14:38,130 --> 00:14:40,740
This is the latest research, by
the way, from Yale University.

318
00:14:40,740 --> 00:14:42,900
This just came
out last December.

319
00:14:42,900 --> 00:14:45,500
So this is very topical.

320
00:14:45,500 --> 00:14:47,300
And when you think
about the people who

321
00:14:47,300 --> 00:14:53,450
are interested in knowing
more with news stories,

322
00:14:53,450 --> 00:14:55,650
and they want to know whether
it's happening or not,

323
00:14:55,650 --> 00:14:58,020
74% of the population, when
you look at the country,

324
00:14:58,020 --> 00:15:00,930
it's not blue and red,
it's not polarized.

325
00:15:00,930 --> 00:15:03,030
It seems like a vast
majority of people,

326
00:15:03,030 --> 00:15:07,370
even in states that don't have
a lot of knowledge about climate

327
00:15:07,370 --> 00:15:11,430
change or maybe dismissive about
the idea of climate change,

328
00:15:11,430 --> 00:15:13,020
they are engaged here.

329
00:15:13,020 --> 00:15:14,400
They want to know.

330
00:15:14,400 --> 00:15:17,200
And when you think about what
stories they want to hear about,

331
00:15:17,200 --> 00:15:20,630
[CHUCKLES] it is
interesting at the bottom--

332
00:15:20,630 --> 00:15:22,850
candidates for president.

333
00:15:22,850 --> 00:15:24,810
And it's interesting,
at the very bottom.

334
00:15:24,810 --> 00:15:27,820
Presidential candidates' plan
in response to global warming.

335
00:15:27,820 --> 00:15:30,840
76% of the population wants
to know more about that?

336
00:15:30,840 --> 00:15:32,490
I find that intriguing, too.

337
00:15:32,490 --> 00:15:36,740
But generally, again,
the minority of people

338
00:15:36,740 --> 00:15:39,280
are not at all interested, 20%.

339
00:15:39,280 --> 00:15:44,140
And that's across the board
in news about climate change.

340
00:15:44,140 --> 00:15:47,210
Katharine Hayhoe, a very
famous climate scientist,

341
00:15:47,210 --> 00:15:50,260
had a great quote.

342
00:15:50,260 --> 00:15:51,980
I mean, she balances what?

343
00:15:51,980 --> 00:15:56,150
Life, and career, and faith,
which is involved in science,

344
00:15:56,150 --> 00:15:59,510
and that cross, that is very
difficult to actually balance.

345
00:15:59,510 --> 00:16:00,230
She had a quote.

346
00:16:00,230 --> 00:16:01,810
She said, "The biggest
problem we have is not

347
00:16:01,810 --> 00:16:03,518
the people who willfully
decide to reject

348
00:16:03,518 --> 00:16:05,120
200 years of basic science.

349
00:16:05,120 --> 00:16:08,090
The bigger problem is the number
of people who say it's real,

350
00:16:08,090 --> 00:16:10,660
but don't do anything about
it and don't think it matters

351
00:16:10,660 --> 00:16:11,830
to them."

352
00:16:11,830 --> 00:16:15,410
That's a vast, vast gap
that we have to close.

353
00:16:15,410 --> 00:16:17,930
And that's the issue,
going forward, too.

354
00:16:17,930 --> 00:16:22,490
So our issue is obviously
tapping into that.

355
00:16:22,490 --> 00:16:23,570
But we live in a bubble.

356
00:16:23,570 --> 00:16:25,780
We come to these conferences,
and we talk about it,

357
00:16:25,780 --> 00:16:28,090
and then we leave, and we
go, oh, that felt good,

358
00:16:28,090 --> 00:16:29,390
because we're with our tribe.

359
00:16:29,390 --> 00:16:30,470
We're very tribal.

360
00:16:30,470 --> 00:16:31,760
We're with our people.

361
00:16:31,760 --> 00:16:32,960
We have backup.

362
00:16:32,960 --> 00:16:34,850
We have common interests.

363
00:16:34,850 --> 00:16:38,295
But obviously, there's 72%,
73% of the population that

364
00:16:38,295 --> 00:16:40,420
still wants to know something
about climate change.

365
00:16:40,420 --> 00:16:43,310
When you look at it in
a statewide perspective,

366
00:16:43,310 --> 00:16:45,800
it comes down to the
blue and the orange here.

367
00:16:45,800 --> 00:16:49,150
And you can see, some states
are dismissive of the idea.

368
00:16:49,150 --> 00:16:51,500
And then here's the
tribalism involved.

369
00:16:51,500 --> 00:16:54,490
Then you go down to the county
level and the little fiefdoms

370
00:16:54,490 --> 00:16:55,070
in there.

371
00:16:55,070 --> 00:16:57,290
And everybody just
squirrels away.

372
00:16:57,290 --> 00:17:01,510
So it's about just homogenizing
the whole conversation

373
00:17:01,510 --> 00:17:04,660
and bringing it out
there, and also making

374
00:17:04,660 --> 00:17:08,030
it accessible to people
who really want to know.

375
00:17:08,030 --> 00:17:09,849
And I think, by
staying in our groups

376
00:17:09,849 --> 00:17:14,329
and staying within our
own like-minded people,

377
00:17:14,329 --> 00:17:17,890
that we miss that
opportunity, I think.

378
00:17:17,890 --> 00:17:20,710
And then the estimated
people, the adults

379
00:17:20,710 --> 00:17:22,550
who think global
warming is happening,

380
00:17:22,550 --> 00:17:24,619
wow, that's also pretty
enlightening too.

381
00:17:24,619 --> 00:17:28,040
Again, in the 70%
change, in the 70%.

382
00:17:28,040 --> 00:17:31,100
So that is the
challenge, going forward.

383
00:17:31,100 --> 00:17:34,750
And obviously, it can be
a very difficult thing

384
00:17:34,750 --> 00:17:38,030
too, when you're talking about
trying to change someone's mind.

385
00:17:38,030 --> 00:17:40,130
There are people you will
never change their mind,

386
00:17:40,130 --> 00:17:41,450
and I've run into those.

387
00:17:41,450 --> 00:17:44,540
And so it's a waste of time
to engage in that sense too.

388
00:17:44,540 --> 00:17:46,940
So there's a limit to
what we can tolerate,

389
00:17:46,940 --> 00:17:50,170
anybody can tolerate.

390
00:17:50,170 --> 00:17:53,620
It's a crazy thing
too, because some

391
00:17:53,620 --> 00:17:55,505
of those that you
don't reach again

392
00:17:55,505 --> 00:17:57,130
will want to come
after you, especially

393
00:17:57,130 --> 00:17:58,370
if you're in the media.

394
00:17:58,370 --> 00:18:01,750
But I find it interesting too
as the next generation moving up

395
00:18:01,750 --> 00:18:03,502
is not really fazed by that.

396
00:18:03,502 --> 00:18:05,210
They're still formulating
their opinions,

397
00:18:05,210 --> 00:18:07,990
they're still with the idea
of what they believe in.

398
00:18:07,990 --> 00:18:10,460
And what they believe in
is, the planet is warming.

399
00:18:10,460 --> 00:18:11,630
We're going to do
something about it.

400
00:18:11,630 --> 00:18:13,213
My generation wasn't
really like that,

401
00:18:13,213 --> 00:18:15,140
and I feel weird about that.

402
00:18:15,140 --> 00:18:17,440
But also, it does mean
that there's a lot of work

403
00:18:17,440 --> 00:18:18,380
ahead, right?

404
00:18:18,380 --> 00:18:21,260
And to quote another famous
professor, Professor Dumbledore,

405
00:18:21,260 --> 00:18:24,587
for those who like Harry Potter,
"Dark times lie ahead of us.

406
00:18:24,587 --> 00:18:26,920
There will be a time when we
must choose between what is

407
00:18:26,920 --> 00:18:28,700
right and what is easy."

408
00:18:28,700 --> 00:18:30,470
Obviously, it's
not an easy task.

409
00:18:30,470 --> 00:18:33,310
There's a lot of work ahead,
and there's a lot of dark times.

410
00:18:33,310 --> 00:18:36,970
And that can be a little bit
more on the anxiety level.

411
00:18:36,970 --> 00:18:39,450
And that is a big thing too.

412
00:18:39,450 --> 00:18:41,890
Doomism is a thing
in climate change.

413
00:18:41,890 --> 00:18:44,920
If you go, and you
doomscroll, as they say,

414
00:18:44,920 --> 00:18:49,330
the climate discussions,
the job is overwhelming.

415
00:18:49,330 --> 00:18:50,970
You can fall into
a spiral, and there

416
00:18:50,970 --> 00:18:52,178
can be no coming out of that.

417
00:18:52,178 --> 00:18:54,120
Climate anxiety
isn't dismissive,

418
00:18:54,120 --> 00:18:56,950
and it shouldn't be
dismissed, it's apparent.

419
00:18:56,950 --> 00:19:02,400
And it, honestly, can fall on
the lines of race and gender

420
00:19:02,400 --> 00:19:04,050
too.

421
00:19:04,050 --> 00:19:06,300
This graphic too, also
from Yale University,

422
00:19:06,300 --> 00:19:09,120
shows that Latinos
are mostly affected

423
00:19:09,120 --> 00:19:15,717
by this, 17% of those who
think it's an overall issue.

424
00:19:15,717 --> 00:19:18,300
And some of that is severe, some
of it is moderate, some of it

425
00:19:18,300 --> 00:19:18,940
is mild.

426
00:19:18,940 --> 00:19:25,350
Gen Z, there you are, and the
millennials, male versus female.

427
00:19:25,350 --> 00:19:30,030
Gen X, honestly, do throw
the weight of my generation

428
00:19:30,030 --> 00:19:31,030
upon my shoulders.

429
00:19:31,030 --> 00:19:33,400
It does feel like, we
saw the train coming.

430
00:19:33,400 --> 00:19:36,060
We heard the sirens,
the gate went down,

431
00:19:36,060 --> 00:19:37,480
and we didn't do much about it.

432
00:19:37,480 --> 00:19:41,850
It feels like we didn't
really get engaged.

433
00:19:41,850 --> 00:19:45,355
Not to defend it, but some of it
might have been the fact that we

434
00:19:45,355 --> 00:19:47,230
didn't have a lot of
information in the '90s.

435
00:19:47,230 --> 00:19:49,480
I remember going to conferences,
and it was just like,

436
00:19:49,480 --> 00:19:51,738
we sat around and were
like, we're pretty certain,

437
00:19:51,738 --> 00:19:53,530
it's warming, but our
models weren't great.

438
00:19:53,530 --> 00:19:55,080
They didn't simulate the
atmosphere as well as

439
00:19:55,080 --> 00:19:56,910
they do now, which is
all the more reason

440
00:19:56,910 --> 00:19:59,932
to believe the data, right?

441
00:19:59,932 --> 00:20:01,890
And it is funny too,
because I saw the program,

442
00:20:01,890 --> 00:20:04,720
and I saw, it said, Pete
Bouchard, climate activist.

443
00:20:04,720 --> 00:20:06,790
And I'm like, I had
to pause for a second.

444
00:20:06,790 --> 00:20:08,680
I thought, am I really?

445
00:20:08,680 --> 00:20:10,150
Have I really done enough?

446
00:20:10,150 --> 00:20:12,700
I mean, I go to conferences,
I speak about it a lot.

447
00:20:12,700 --> 00:20:14,940
But it is something
that you think back,

448
00:20:14,940 --> 00:20:17,410
and there's always
something you could do more.

449
00:20:17,410 --> 00:20:19,930
You can always really
take up the cause.

450
00:20:19,930 --> 00:20:22,710
And again, it's your
generation inspiring

451
00:20:22,710 --> 00:20:25,560
mine and inspiring me to
come to these conferences

452
00:20:25,560 --> 00:20:27,570
and talk to you about it too.

453
00:20:27,570 --> 00:20:33,020
But anxiety, and climate,
psychological distress

454
00:20:33,020 --> 00:20:36,830
is also something, I think, that
is playing a role in what we're

455
00:20:36,830 --> 00:20:38,390
seeing now with
social media and how

456
00:20:38,390 --> 00:20:41,190
we perceive how we're
going to go forward,

457
00:20:41,190 --> 00:20:43,460
how we're going to attack
this whole subject matter.

458
00:20:43,460 --> 00:20:45,770
And it is necessary
for you to find help

459
00:20:45,770 --> 00:20:47,370
if it really does bother you.

460
00:20:47,370 --> 00:20:49,890
And it's OK to step back, right?

461
00:20:49,890 --> 00:20:51,270
I do woodworking on the side.

462
00:20:51,270 --> 00:20:52,853
And sometimes, I get
really tangled up

463
00:20:52,853 --> 00:20:56,582
in some of the geometry or
the joinery that I'm doing.

464
00:20:56,582 --> 00:20:58,290
And I actually have
to step away from it.

465
00:20:58,290 --> 00:20:58,890
And I come back to it.

466
00:20:58,890 --> 00:21:00,510
And I go, wow, what
was I thinking?

467
00:21:00,510 --> 00:21:01,010
Right?

468
00:21:01,010 --> 00:21:04,520
Because that can be something
that can be regenerating to you.

469
00:21:04,520 --> 00:21:05,870
And fall back on your peers too.

470
00:21:05,870 --> 00:21:08,280
That tribalism,
that's your core.

471
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:10,340
When you go out
there in the open,

472
00:21:10,340 --> 00:21:12,530
and you're expanding
your horizons,

473
00:21:12,530 --> 00:21:15,710
and you're confronting these
people, it's OK to fall back

474
00:21:15,710 --> 00:21:17,960
and say, hang on,
I need a second.

475
00:21:17,960 --> 00:21:19,910
So if the planet
could speak to us,

476
00:21:19,910 --> 00:21:21,660
what do you think it
would say these days?

477
00:21:21,660 --> 00:21:22,160
Right?

478
00:21:22,160 --> 00:21:25,280
If we personified the
planet, it probably

479
00:21:25,280 --> 00:21:28,590
would say, what are you doing?

480
00:21:28,590 --> 00:21:31,950
And also, does it feel a
little warm in here to you?

481
00:21:31,950 --> 00:21:32,583
Right?

482
00:21:32,583 --> 00:21:34,500
Those are the things
that you can think about.

483
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:38,000
But also, it might
be saying, thank you.

484
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:41,960
For the people who are
doing the work out there,

485
00:21:41,960 --> 00:21:45,770
stay hopeful, and
don't give up hope.

486
00:21:45,770 --> 00:21:46,370
Thanks.

